We talk about three things, and
that's speed, security,

00:20:49.630 --> 00:20:50.410
simplicity.

00:20:50.410 --> 00:20:53.210
And I think you touched a little
bit on security and

00:20:53.210 --> 00:20:55.710
simplicity of getting photos up
there, simplicity of being

00:20:55.710 --> 00:20:57.180
able to post.

00:20:57.180 --> 00:20:58.190
What about speed?

00:20:58.190 --> 00:20:59.190
How do you measure
if something's

00:20:59.190 --> 00:21:00.090
happening quick enough?

00:21:00.090 --> 00:21:01.450
What is a good load time?

00:21:01.450 --> 00:21:02.490
How does that impact you guys?

00:21:02.490 --> 00:21:05.170
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: We care so
deeply about latency and

00:21:05.170 --> 00:21:07.460
speed, and it's across
a number of levels.

00:21:07.460 --> 00:21:11.700
One is just page load time being
as efficient as we can,

00:21:11.700 --> 00:21:13.840
making sure we're doing
things right.

00:21:13.840 --> 00:21:15.860
I know there's lots of sessions
here, but our

00:21:15.860 --> 00:21:19.470
internal hygiene there is
rigorous and we care deeply

00:21:19.470 --> 00:21:19.980
about that.

00:21:19.980 --> 00:21:23.150
It's everything from how the
system's architected to how

00:21:23.150 --> 00:21:25.180
the page is rendering in
specific browsers.

00:21:25.180 --> 00:21:27.470
So that's one aspect of speed.

00:21:27.470 --> 00:21:30.000
Another is for things like--

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:32.850
I haven't even gone through the
features of autoenhancing

00:21:32.850 --> 00:21:35.770
your images, but these are
compute intensive features,

00:21:35.770 --> 00:21:39.100
and so thinking about how we
take advantage of Google's

00:21:39.100 --> 00:21:42.710
Global Compute Infrastructure
to do that in a way that is

00:21:42.710 --> 00:21:45.930
efficient is another aspect,
making sure the algorithms are

00:21:45.930 --> 00:21:49.630
efficient, making sure that
users' expectations are in

00:21:49.630 --> 00:21:52.530
line with what we can deliver,
all of these things.

00:21:52.530 --> 00:21:55.190
For instance, auto hashtagging,
one thing the

00:21:55.190 --> 00:21:57.540
team struggled with is could
we do it in real time?

00:21:57.540 --> 00:22:00.350
Could you post something and
have the post drop into your

00:22:00.350 --> 00:22:02.960
stream with the hashtags
directly on it?

00:22:02.960 --> 00:22:05.460
That was a big challenge because
what we wanted, again,

00:22:05.460 --> 00:22:07.970
in deference to the content
owner, we didn't want you to

00:22:07.970 --> 00:22:11.610
have to come back tomorrow to
see how your post was tagged.

00:22:11.610 --> 00:22:13.610
We wanted that to
be real time.

00:22:13.610 --> 00:22:15.030
LOUIS GRAY: You don't want to
go back and fix it five

00:22:15.030 --> 00:22:16.895
minutes later or five hours
later or any of that stuff.

00:22:16.895 --> 00:22:18.120
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: It had
to be interactive.

00:22:18.120 --> 00:22:22.200
And so speed is, throughout
our product, of foremost

00:22:22.200 --> 00:22:26.370
concern and we think about it
deeply and in subtle ways and

00:22:26.370 --> 00:22:30.130
in the forefront of what a lot
of our teams are working on.

00:22:30.130 --> 00:22:31.600
LOUIS GRAY: And one of the other
forefront pieces you've

00:22:31.600 --> 00:22:34.195
got is Hangouts.

00:22:34.195 --> 00:22:37.410
I always used to say Hangouts
is kind of that hammer that

00:22:37.410 --> 00:22:38.190
hits all the nails.

00:22:38.190 --> 00:22:40.650
It's just been an exciting thing
that Google+ had that

00:22:40.650 --> 00:22:42.840
was a significant
differentiator, and it's been

00:22:42.840 --> 00:22:43.960
there since day one.

00:22:43.960 --> 00:22:47.190
And Hangouts has really grown
into something else now.

00:22:47.190 --> 00:22:50.300
We have the On Air capability,
and the new app that launched

00:22:50.300 --> 00:22:53.010
yesterday which really unifies
a lot of our messaging.

00:22:53.010 --> 00:22:54.070
So let's talk about that.

00:22:54.070 --> 00:22:55.500
I definitely don't want
to miss that.

00:22:55.500 --> 00:22:57.250
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: OK.

00:22:57.250 --> 00:23:00.010
There's so many more photo
features I would love to talk

00:23:00.010 --> 00:23:02.230
about but in the interest of
time, I'll take your lead and

00:23:02.230 --> 00:23:04.610
we'll talk about Hangouts.

00:23:04.610 --> 00:23:06.940
Hangouts is an incredibly
beautiful,

00:23:06.940 --> 00:23:09.820
simple and subtle product.

00:23:09.820 --> 00:23:11.960
I'm really proud of the team.

00:23:11.960 --> 00:23:15.030
It took a lot of craft and
discipline from a product

00:23:15.030 --> 00:23:18.230
standpoint to build something
that just works.

00:23:18.230 --> 00:23:22.970
It's not the sort of wow factor
of, enhance your photos

00:23:22.970 --> 00:23:25.360
or automatically hashtag
something.

00:23:25.360 --> 00:23:28.530
It is just a beautiful,
thoughtful, convenient product

00:23:28.530 --> 00:23:31.350
experience that just works
like it should.

00:23:31.350 --> 00:23:35.790
One of the things Vic took you
through was a matrix, and

00:23:35.790 --> 00:23:38.760
aren't there already products
that fulfill this?

00:23:38.760 --> 00:23:39.220
And the truth is--

00:23:39.220 --> 00:23:40.710
LOUIS GRAY: I've been able to
send you a chat before, I've

00:23:40.710 --> 00:23:42.580
been able to send you photos
before, but I think that

00:23:42.580 --> 00:23:45.950
matrix essentially shows photos,
videos, and text

00:23:45.950 --> 00:23:47.740
across different devices--

00:23:47.740 --> 00:23:50.860
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Single
user, multi-user.

00:23:50.860 --> 00:23:51.120
LOUIS GRAY: They're talking
about three

00:23:51.120 --> 00:23:52.680
dimensions now, Bradley.

00:23:52.680 --> 00:23:54.190
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Yeah,
it's a cube.

00:23:54.190 --> 00:23:56.800
There really is no product
that met all of those

00:23:56.800 --> 00:23:57.630
requirements.

00:23:57.630 --> 00:24:00.380
And I really think we've nailed
it and we're going to

00:24:00.380 --> 00:24:02.900
put something in everyone's
pocket, irrespective of

00:24:02.900 --> 00:24:05.590
device, or in front
of everyone.

00:24:05.590 --> 00:24:06.760
Maybe it's not your pocket.

00:24:06.760 --> 00:24:10.130
Maybe it's on your face or
maybe it's on your desk.

00:24:10.130 --> 00:24:12.230
But we're going to put it
everywhere you need it.

00:24:12.230 --> 00:24:16.290
And it will be the simplest
way to really connect to

00:24:16.290 --> 00:24:20.350
another person, whether that's
text, photos, emoji, or real

00:24:20.350 --> 00:24:23.930
time, face-to-face interaction
between groups of people.

00:24:23.930 --> 00:24:25.930
We are going to span
that entire gamut.

00:24:25.930 --> 00:24:28.800
And for Google, I think
distribution has never been

00:24:28.800 --> 00:24:29.620
our problem.

00:24:29.620 --> 00:24:32.990
If we had a great product, we
have an opportunity to get

00:24:32.990 --> 00:24:35.940
that in people's hands, and I
don't think we've stepped up

00:24:35.940 --> 00:24:38.400
and created the right product
until yesterday

00:24:38.400 --> 00:24:39.090
and we now have that.

00:24:39.090 --> 00:24:40.000
LOUIS GRAY: Solving these
problems are hard.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:42.090
I think one of the behind the
scenes, I think [INAUDIBLE]

00:24:42.090 --> 00:24:45.140
did a big run through of
the Hangouts creation.

00:24:45.140 --> 00:24:47.660
It's a challenge to take the
many different products that

00:24:47.660 --> 00:24:50.400
we have and make a beautiful,
seamless user experience like

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:53.010
Larry often talks about, and
Vic often talks about.

00:24:53.010 --> 00:24:55.100
And so we've seen that with
Google+, we're seeing it again

00:24:55.100 --> 00:24:56.080
with Hangouts.

00:24:56.080 --> 00:24:57.940
And one interesting thing about
Hangouts, because it's

00:24:57.940 --> 00:25:01.880
such a shining star of Google+,
it's gotten a lot of

00:25:01.880 --> 00:25:04.160
attention but it's also gotten
a lot of real world use that

00:25:04.160 --> 00:25:06.680
kind of goes unspoken.

00:25:06.680 --> 00:25:09.400
When I was in Europe, I did a
Hangout with my kids and my

00:25:09.400 --> 00:25:11.200
wife every single day.

00:25:11.200 --> 00:25:12.380
We were separated by what?

00:25:12.380 --> 00:25:16.640
6,000 miles, give or take, eight
or nine hours, and every

00:25:16.640 --> 00:25:18.380
day I spoke face to face
with my kids and

00:25:18.380 --> 00:25:19.620
they just expect it.

00:25:19.620 --> 00:25:23.510
They've come to believe that
they can pick up a Nexus 7,

00:25:23.510 --> 00:25:25.820
ask Google anything, get the
answer they want, connect with

00:25:25.820 --> 00:25:27.290
anyone, anytime.

00:25:27.290 --> 00:25:30.050
I mean, just even simple things
like getting a movie on

00:25:30.050 --> 00:25:33.110
Google Play on instant, it's
incredible what they believe.

00:25:33.110 --> 00:25:34.020
And you look at Hangouts--

00:25:34.020 --> 00:25:36.560
even last night after we wrapped
up at seven o'clock, I

00:25:36.560 --> 00:25:40.550
went to the hotel and my wife
sent me a message on Hangout

00:25:40.550 --> 00:25:41.690
that says, can we do
a Hangout now?

00:25:41.690 --> 00:25:44.730
I said sure, and got to talk to
my kids and tell them all

00:25:44.730 --> 00:25:47.060
to go to bed and pick
up their toys.

00:25:47.060 --> 00:25:49.220
So how has Hangouts really
changed the way that you

00:25:49.220 --> 00:25:51.570
collaborate, either at
work or at home?

00:25:51.570 --> 00:25:54.070
Are you still having fun just
hitting the Hangout button and

00:25:54.070 --> 00:25:56.140
waiting for people?

00:25:56.140 --> 00:25:57.580
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: It's changed
it dramatically.

00:25:57.580 --> 00:25:59.980
I think as you're pointing
out, we have these high

00:25:59.980 --> 00:26:01.310
profile Hangouts On Air.

00:26:01.310 --> 00:26:04.090
We have the President, and the
Dalai Lama and chiefs of

00:26:04.090 --> 00:26:04.680
state, and--

00:26:04.680 --> 00:26:05.980
LOUIS GRAY: All the way
down to my kids.

00:26:05.980 --> 00:26:06.740
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Yes, right.

00:26:06.740 --> 00:26:10.870
So that stuff gets the attention
a lot of times.

00:26:10.870 --> 00:26:14.160
But what is more exciting to
me is people just using

00:26:14.160 --> 00:26:18.130
Hangouts in this private,
important way to connect to

00:26:18.130 --> 00:26:18.770
other people.

00:26:18.770 --> 00:26:22.100
So the use case you talked
about I experience

00:26:22.100 --> 00:26:23.190
myself all the time.

00:26:23.190 --> 00:26:25.740
When I'm traveling, it's the
best way to connect face to

00:26:25.740 --> 00:26:29.510
face with the family and have
an authentic, great

00:26:29.510 --> 00:26:29.960
connection.

00:26:29.960 --> 00:26:33.200
It's so much better
than a call.

00:26:33.200 --> 00:26:34.690
You hand the phone to the
kids, and they don't

00:26:34.690 --> 00:26:36.390
even want to talk.

00:26:36.390 --> 00:26:40.150
But if you can see them, and
I'm often using the Effects

00:26:40.150 --> 00:26:41.480
and we're having fun.

00:26:41.480 --> 00:26:42.750
We're laughing, we're
interacting,

00:26:42.750 --> 00:26:44.540
it's real, it's visceral.

00:26:44.540 --> 00:26:47.160
So I'm a fan of that use case.

00:26:47.160 --> 00:26:49.480
But you pointed out at work.

00:26:49.480 --> 00:26:54.340
One of our leaders, Shi Chu,
who was the VP under whom

00:26:54.340 --> 00:26:57.470
Hangouts was built, mentioned
in the previous session that

00:26:57.470 --> 00:27:02.420
Google itself conducts more than
20,000 Hangouts a day.

00:27:02.420 --> 00:27:05.190
So this has become an integral
piece of our own workflow.

00:27:05.190 --> 00:27:08.320
We can't get through the day
without using Hangouts to

00:27:08.320 --> 00:27:11.620
connect to our distributed
offices and actually

00:27:11.620 --> 00:27:12.830
get our jobs done.

00:27:12.830 --> 00:27:15.470
So it's not only for fun and
giggles and laughs and

00:27:15.470 --> 00:27:16.980
connection with the family.

00:27:16.980 --> 00:27:17.920
It's for serious work.

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:19.780
We actually use screen
sharing, we do our

00:27:19.780 --> 00:27:23.240
presentations this way, we
interact as teams over

00:27:23.240 --> 00:27:27.030
Hangouts, and it's really
spanning the gamut of

00:27:27.030 --> 00:27:30.430
communication, everything from
the ridiculous to the sublime.

00:27:30.430 --> 00:27:34.380
And so it's a part of my daily
life every day of my life.

00:27:37.090 --> 00:27:38.350
LOUIS GRAY: So one of the things
we talked about, we

00:27:38.350 --> 00:27:39.550
talked about Interests.

00:27:39.550 --> 00:27:43.790
How do people factor into
Google+ and Google at large?

00:27:43.790 --> 00:27:45.980
I mean, I know there's a kind
of what would be called a

00:27:45.980 --> 00:27:49.490
rallying cry or really the
genesis of Google+.

00:27:49.490 --> 00:27:51.130
It wasn't just that you
had a lot of people

00:27:51.130 --> 00:27:53.050
who wanted some work.

00:27:53.050 --> 00:27:56.335
What has sparked that, and how
is that continuing today?

00:27:56.335 --> 00:27:58.900
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Well, I love
the way Vic put it yesterday

00:27:58.900 --> 00:27:59.530
in his keynote.

00:27:59.530 --> 00:28:03.640
He said technology should get
out of the way so that we can

00:28:03.640 --> 00:28:07.980
do what we're really here to
do-- live, learn, and love.

00:28:07.980 --> 00:28:10.220
Those are the things that are
important in people's lives

00:28:10.220 --> 00:28:13.440
and technology should not be
a bright, shiny object that

00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:14.500
detracts from that.

00:28:14.500 --> 00:28:17.620
On the contrary, it should
empower that and enable that,

00:28:17.620 --> 00:28:20.990
and that's what we're trying
to do at Google writ large,

00:28:20.990 --> 00:28:23.730
but also at Google+, is sort of
get the technology out of

00:28:23.730 --> 00:28:26.900
the way and allow that
connection to happen.

00:28:26.900 --> 00:28:30.560
And it informs our design, it
informs our product direction,

00:28:30.560 --> 00:28:31.710
and it informs the thinking.

00:28:31.710 --> 00:28:34.340
One of the things I
loved yesterday--

00:28:34.340 --> 00:28:41.020
it was a long keynote, but the
thread of people and of

00:28:41.020 --> 00:28:44.490
living, learning, loving, and
the connection was present

00:28:44.490 --> 00:28:47.340
throughout every presenter's
moment up there.

00:28:47.340 --> 00:28:48.440
LOUIS GRAY: Concluding
with Larry.

00:28:48.440 --> 00:28:50.150
I think one of the things we've
touched on a few times

00:28:50.150 --> 00:28:53.680
with GDL at I/O is at Google,
we actually have an

00:28:53.680 --> 00:28:56.050
opportunity to hear from Larry
about once a week,

00:28:56.050 --> 00:28:57.540
some people even more.

00:28:57.540 --> 00:29:00.630
And the interesting thing about
Larry is he doesn't talk

00:29:00.630 --> 00:29:03.550
about product, details,
and features and get

00:29:03.550 --> 00:29:03.940
deep down in it.

00:29:03.940 --> 00:29:07.400
He talks about the way that it
can transform humanity, and

00:29:07.400 --> 00:29:09.990
the opportunity that's available
through technology,

00:29:09.990 --> 00:29:12.300
and the things that Google
should be doing.

00:29:12.300 --> 00:29:14.730
And I thought it was a real
pleasure to see that kind of

00:29:14.730 --> 00:29:18.130
direct access to Larry by all
the developers who are here

00:29:18.130 --> 00:29:20.520
and those who are watching on
the Live Stream as well.

00:29:20.520 --> 00:29:23.110
And I think the type of things
you're talking about, which

00:29:23.110 --> 00:29:27.780
are very emotive and feeling
oriented, are something that

00:29:27.780 --> 00:29:30.270
has been a key for Google+ from
the beginning and we're

00:29:30.270 --> 00:29:31.980
really seeing comes
from the very top.

00:29:31.980 --> 00:29:33.080
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Yeah,
it really does.

00:29:33.080 --> 00:29:35.580
And you said he doesn't
get into the details.

00:29:35.580 --> 00:29:39.280
He actually does, and he has got
fantastic insights at that

00:29:39.280 --> 00:29:40.040
level, too.

00:29:40.040 --> 00:29:41.190
But I think you're right.

00:29:41.190 --> 00:29:47.260
What is thrilling is to be a
part of that vision, to think

00:29:47.260 --> 00:29:49.740
about the way that Larry thinks
about the problems, to

00:29:49.740 --> 00:29:53.710
catch some of that yesterday
when he was saying things

00:29:53.710 --> 00:29:55.970
like, "we should be building
products that don't yet

00:29:55.970 --> 00:29:57.620
exist."

00:29:57.620 --> 00:30:01.920
It is so natural for us as
humans to gravitate to the

00:30:01.920 --> 00:30:05.160
comfortable, the known, to think
of things in reference

00:30:05.160 --> 00:30:08.170
to other things, and we don't
even realize how much that

00:30:08.170 --> 00:30:10.000
inhibits our creativity.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:14.080
And Larry is just masterful
at breaking through those

00:30:14.080 --> 00:30:17.170
constraints and barriers and
upleveling people's thinking

00:30:17.170 --> 00:30:18.770
to greatness.

00:30:18.770 --> 00:30:21.480
He's a really great model
of that, but he

00:30:21.480 --> 00:30:25.080
also inspires others.

00:30:25.080 --> 00:30:28.990
And so I was thrilled that he
had a chance to literally

00:30:28.990 --> 00:30:33.630
inspire millions yesterday and
give people a taste of what

00:30:33.630 --> 00:30:36.550
it's like to work with
him and for him.

00:30:36.550 --> 00:30:37.460
LOUIS GRAY: It was
exceptional.

00:30:37.460 --> 00:30:38.340
I'm glad you touched on that.

